of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Rugeley (Staffs). The place, recorded as Rugelie in 1086 (   Domesday Book  ), is named with Old English  <i>hrycg</i> ‘ridge’ +  <i>lēah</i> ‘(woodland) clearing, glade’."],"variants":[{"name":"Ridgely","meanings":["English (Berkshire and Buckinghamshire): variant of   Ridgley  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Domesday Book","meanings":["English, Welsh: locative name, apparently from Humby (Lincs) or Hanby in Welton (Lincs); the latter is recorded as  <i>Humbi</i> in   Domesday Book  ."]},{"name":"Rudgeley","meanings":["English:  see  Rugeley  ."]},{"name":"Ridgley","meanings":["English (Buckinghamshire): habitational name from Rugeley (Staffordshire), from Old English <i>hrycg</i> ‘ridge’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’."]},{"name":"Rudgley","meanings":["English:  see  Rugeley  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Rugeley was born in 1461, in Warwickshire, England. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Alice Clarkson. He died after 1510."},"et":{"1461–after 1510":"1461–pärast 1510","1470–1510":"1470–1510","1486–1558":"1486–1558","1490–1554":"1490–1554","1511–1581":"1511